<webwork-reps version="2" webwork2_major_version="2" webwork2_minor_version="20" xml:id="extracted-section-quadratic-graphs-and-vertex-form-8-1-9" assembly-id="section-quadratic-graphs-and-vertex-form-8-1-9">
  <static seed="1077" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/Factoring/factoring375.pg">
    <statement><p>Factor the given polynomial.</p>
<p><m>{2y^{2}+20y+18}=</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>2\mathopen{}\left(y+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+9\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Let<rsq/>s start by noting that <m>2</m> is a common factor to each term, so 
we may write</p>
<p><m>{2y^{2}+20y+18}={2\mathopen{}\left(y^{2}+10y+9\right)}</m></p>
<p>To factor this expression further we make the following observations:
<ul label="disc">
<li>
<p>the leading coefficient is 1</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the middle term<rsq/>s coefficient and the last term are <em>positive</em> which means that the factorization
will have the form</p>
<p><m>(y+\phantom{3})(y+\phantom{3})</m></p>
</li>
</ul></p>
<p>We look for factors of <m>9</m> that add to <m>10</m>; the 
factors that work are <m>1</m> and <m>9</m> so</p>
<p><m>{2y^{2}+20y+18}={2\mathopen{}\left(y+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+9\right)}</m></p>
<p>Note that this answer can be checked by using the FOIL (<alert>F</alert>irst <alert>O</alert>utside <alert>I</alert>nside <alert>L</alert>ast) technique (exercise).</p>
</solution>
